# Constant Fold NULL Propagation

## Description

Propagates NULL through strict functions (functions where any NULL
argument produces a NULL result). Most SQL functions are strict by
default. ABS(NULL) -> NULL, CONCAT('a', NULL) -> NULL (in some
databases), NULL + 5 -> NULL.

**When to apply**: Strict function with any NULL constant argument.

**Why it works**: SQL three-valued logic specifies that strict
functions return NULL when any argument is NULL.

## Implementation

```rust
rw!("null-prop-unary";
    "(?f null)" => "null"
    if is_strict("?f")
),
rw!("null-prop-binary-left";
    "(?f null ?b)" => "null"
    if is_strict("?f")
),
rw!("null-prop-binary-right";
    "(?f ?a null)" => "null"
    if is_strict("?f")
),
rw!("null-comparison";
    "(= ?x null)" => "null"
),
rw!("null-arithmetic";
    "(+ ?x null)" => "null"
),
```

## Preconditions

Non-strict functions (COALESCE, NULLIF, IS NULL, IS NOT NULL) are excluded.

## Test Cases

```sql
-- Before
SELECT ABS(NULL) FROM t;
-- After
SELECT NULL FROM t;
```

```sql
-- Negative: COALESCE is not strict
SELECT COALESCE(NULL, 5) FROM t;
-- Stays: COALESCE(NULL, 5) -> 5 (handled by coalesce folding)
```

